node.text:
It’s been a while since I’ve done and update and today happens to be three years since the crash that should have killed me. 
.
.
.
My recovery has been nothing short of a miracle and I am incredibly lucky to be where I am in it and to be able to do what I currently can. 
.
.
.
With that being said I still have some issues I’m dealing with so I figured I’d fill you all in on them. 
.
.
.
The right side of my body was effected more severely from the trauma.  The muscles on my right side spasm a lot more and I’m not able to get them to consistently flex. My right hand is also still having issues with finger dexterity, strength, and overall usage. 
.
.
.
My triceps and pec muscles are still missing the signal from my brain to fire and build so it has been difficult to rebuild my upper body, as you can see by my “super deep” push-ups. 
.
.
.
My legs have been doing pretty great though. Aside from the daily morning spasms that some days make walking difficult, I have regained I’d say about 75 percent of my leg strength back while my arms are lucky to be at about 40-45%. 
.
.
.
Regardless of what I have or haven’t gotten back, I know I am as lucky as a lottery winner to be back this far after what my body went through. 
.
.
.
I simply cannot thank my family, friends, healthcare workers, sponsors, @road2recovery , and all of you internet acquaintances for being there with me through the last three years. 
.
.
I don’t know why I’ve been lucky enough to walk and ride again after what happened, but I do know for a fact that if it wasn’t for all the folks listed above, I wouldn’t be where I am at today. 
.
.
.
So if you are reading this, THANK YOU. Now remind yourself that life is short, enjoy and cherish it. ❤️

I’m very grateful to announce a sponsorship with @pit_viper sunglasses. 
.
.
I know I dont do as cool of activities as I used to, so anytime a company still wants to support me, it means a lot. 
.
.
Good thing my pets still do cool stuff, and love the Vipers. 😂😂
.
.
Stay tuned for some cool projects with Pit Viper coming up… and shoot over to their page now to see a project we did recently. Ever see a limousine hot tub break a world record distance jump?! If not, you can change that answer to a yes by clicking here—-> @pit_viper 
.
.
.
Thank you for the support Pit Viper! 🙏

node.text:
I had a blast ripping Pitbikes around the @vacala515 compound yesterday with @flyinvman107 , Tyler, and BPope. 
.
.
Even though video doesn’t really do it justice, it’s definitely the biggest jumps I’ve hit since I’ve been back to riding. I was scared to hit them at first but before long I was actually moving the bike around and kind of doing “whips”. 
.
.
Cheers to still progressing and making improvements over 3 years later when the docs told me that wherever I was after 6months was where I’d be forever.
.
.
Moral of the story, don’t let what others say about you dictate your life/future… oh, and ride Pitbikes because fun is important. 🤙

.
.
This clip tells the story of our careers. As soon as the snow hits I’d be off the bike and onto the boards while Pat stuck to two wheels (or one) and would ride all winter no matter the temperature. 
.
.
That could have something to do with why he is now an 11 time National Champion and I currently train cats to do skate tricks I can’t do myself anymore… 🤷‍♂️🧐😂😂
.
.
Moral of the story, find something you love to do, and do it as long as humanly possible. 🤙

node.text:
Here’s another clip from my recent @nitrocircus Athlete Content contract. 
.
.
When I signed up to create content for Nitro I was honestly a bit nervous. Nitro Circus has a reputation of posting some of the gnarliest stuff in the world, usually “Worlds Firsts” actually…which is something my current body and situation don’t really do anymore.
.
Before my injury I used to think daily about what worlds first I could do on my bikes and boards, and that was all the motivation I needed to work my butt off for it. 
.
.
Fast forward to current day and my filming is more geared towards “firsts for me since the crash” type of footage, which is a far cry from a “Worlds First”.
.
.
That’s why I was reluctant to take the contract at first. But then instead of relying on my body and what skills I have left, I decided to take it as a creative challenge and use my mind to make up for what my body couldn’t do in order to create worthwhile content. 
.
.
This backyard pump track was the first idea I had that got me feeling like it could be cool enough for Nitro to post. 
.
.
It also got me pumped because a majority of my friends and family said that it would be impossible to pump across the driveway, out into the goat pasture, back over the fence, and back across the driveway. Hearing them throw the word “impossible” around just got me more motivated to make it happen. 
.
.
You can’t really tell in the video but half of this run is uphill and the downhill I had to start with isn’t very big. 
.
.
It took a lot of attempts and many hours of solo shoveling with just the kitties and goats, but as you can see, it worked! 
.
.
I guess the moral of the story is, no matter how banged up or lacking your body is, your mind can overcome most obstacles, even when they are deemed “impossible”. 
.
.
Shred on my friends. 🤙
.
.
Thanks to my brother @pat_smage for the drone footage.

This past weekend at the Ohio AMA MotoTrials nationals was quite eventful. 
.
Friday night I was unable to sleep (a common theme in my life every night but especially before events, anyone have any tips?) 
.
.
That left me struggling to find energy Saturday. I was also pretty nervous because I moved up class since the last time I rode a national and I didn’t know quite what to expect. 
.
.
I ended up being able to fight off the fatigue and finish strong with 1-0-3 point loops, getting the lowest score of my class (that’s the goal in trials). However, I ended up taking too long to finish the event (7 hour time limit and I finished in 7 hours and 18 minutes), so I was given 9 penalty points and that took me from 1st to 6th. 
.
.
While I was pretty bummed on the penalty I was even more stoked to have dabbed less than a bunch of super talented riders.  I’ve never won a national in any class before, so getting so close did kind of sting… but I figured I could just make sure to finish in the time limit Sunday, or so I thought…
.
.
As soon as Sundays event started I could tell my body wasn’t having it. I struggled through the first loop and on section one loop 2 my front tire caught a rock heading downhill to the exit and I didn’t have enough arm strength to stop from going over the handlebars. 
.
.
It was a scary crash as I landed on my neck/head area which is almost the worst case scenario for me. Thankfully my helmet and neck brace did the trick and I was able to get up and ride back to the pits.  I made the decision to end my day there as I knew my body just wasn’t up to it. 
.
.
I know many people question why I still ride after the things I have been through, especially when something like this happens. My answer is because you never know when something bad is going to happen to you, when you’re gonna get hurt, or how it’s going to happen. 95% of people that have had injuries similar to me happen in car crashes, most of the time of no fault of their own.  Almost all of my serious falls after my injury besides this one have been on my feet and not a bike or board.  To me life is too short (unlike this caption) to not spend time doing what you love, while you can.

This photo came up in my memories from a time I was still living in the hospital. I am pretty sure this was the first time I was able to move my arm enough to “flex”. 
.
.
I often get too caught up in life and getting back to where I used to be that I forget to be thankful to be where I am. Since I stopped doing the daily “Smagical Updates” it is harder for me to see my progress on a daily basis.
.
.
This photo instantly reminded me of how far I’ve come. 
.
.
I hope you can use this photo as a way to find something in your personal progression to be grateful for. 🙏
.
.
